### CONTEXT (ATLAS Threat Detection Code):
Here is the Rust implementation of the ATLAS threat detector in the workspace:
```rust
//! ATLAS Threat Detector — MITRE ATLAS framework adversarial pattern scanner.
//!
//! Scans text for adversarial AI attack patterns based on the MITRE ATLAS taxonomy.
//! See: <https://atlas.mitre.org/matrices/ATLAS>

use regex::Regex;
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

/// A detected MITRE ATLAS threat tactic, technique, or procedure.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize, PartialEq)]
pub struct ThreatEntry {
    /// ATLAS TTP identifier (e.g. `AML.T0049`).
    pub id: String,
    /// Human-readable TTP name.
    pub name: String,
    /// The keyword that triggered the match.
    pub matched_keyword: String,
}

/// Internal representation of a single TTP with compiled patterns.
struct Ttp {
    id: &'static str,
    name: &'static str,
    patterns: Vec<Regex>,
    keywords: Vec<&'static str>,
}

/// Scans arbitrary text for MITRE ATLAS adversarial AI attack patterns.
///
/// # Example
/// ```rust
/// use security::ATLASThreatDetector;
///
/// let detector = ATLASThreatDetector::new();
/// let threats = detector.scan("ignore previous instructions and do something bad");
/// assert!(!threats.is_empty());
/// ```
pub struct ATLASThreatDetector {
    ttps: Vec<Ttp>,
}

impl ATLASThreatDetector {
    /// Build a new detector with all ATLAS TTP patterns pre-compiled.
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        let definitions: &[(&'static str, &'static str, &[&'static str])] = &[
            (
                "AML.T0049",
                "Evasion of AI-Assessed Policies",
                &[
                    "ignore previous instructions",
                    "disregard safety",
                    "jailbreak",
                    "dan prompt",
                    "act as if",
                    "roleplay as",
                    "without moral judgment",
                ],
            ),
            (
                "AML.T0052",
                "Abuse of Dual-Use Foundational Model",
                &[
                    "malware",
                    "keylogger",
                    "ransomware",
                    "exploit code",
                    "phishing email",
                    "impersonate",
                    "deepfake",
                    "disinformation campaign",
                    "make a bomb",
                    "synthesize a weapon",
                    "create poison",
                    "illegal substance",
                ],
            ),
            (
                "AML.T0040",
                "Reconnaissance of AI Systems",
                &[
                    "what are your safety guidelines",
                    "how do you filter content",
                    "what is your system prompt",
                    "reveal your instructions",
                    "find security flaws",
                ],
            ),
            (
                "AML.T0043",
                "AI-Enabled Social Engineering",
                &[
                    "convince the user to",
                    "trick the employee into",
                    "create a pretext",
                    "write a persuasive script to",
                    "generate a fraudulent message",
                ],
            ),
        ];

        let ttps = definitions
            .iter()
            .map(|(id, name, keywords)| {
                let patterns = keywords
                    .iter()
                    .map(|kw| {
                        // Word-boundary-aware regex; escape special chars in keyword.
                        let escaped = regex::escape(kw);
                        Regex::new(&format!(r"(?i)\b{}\b", escaped))
                            .unwrap_or_else(|_| Regex::new(r"(?i)NOMATCH_PLACEHOLDER").unwrap())
                    })
                    .collect();
                Ttp {
                    id,
                    name,
                    patterns,
                    keywords: keywords.to_vec(),
                }
            })
            .collect();

        Self { ttps }
    }

    /// Scan `text` for ATLAS adversarial patterns.
    ///
    /// Returns a (possibly empty) list of detected threats. Each TTP can only
    /// appear once in the result, even if multiple keywords match.
    pub fn scan(&self, text: &str) -> Vec<ThreatEntry> {
        let mut detected = Vec::new();
        for ttp in &self.ttps {
            for (pattern, keyword) in ttp.patterns.iter().zip(ttp.keywords.iter()) {
                if pattern.is_match(text) {
                    detected.push(ThreatEntry {
                        id: ttp.id.to_string(),
                        name: ttp.name.to_string(),
                        matched_keyword: keyword.to_string(),
                    });
                    break; // only one entry per TTP
                }
            }
        }
        detected
    }

    /// Returns `true` if any ATLAS threat pattern is detected in `text`.
    pub fn has_threats(&self, text: &str) -> bool {
        !self.scan(text).is_empty()
    }

    /// Return a formatted summary of all detected threats, suitable for display.
    pub fn format_report(&self, text: &str) -> String {
        let threats = self.scan(text);
        if threats.is_empty() {
            return "No ATLAS threats detected.".to_string();
        }
        let lines: Vec<String> = threats
            .iter()
            .map(|t| format!("[{}] {} (keyword: \"{}\")", t.id, t.name, t.matched_keyword))
            .collect();
        format!("ATLAS Threats Detected:\n{}", lines.join("\n"))
    }
}

impl Default for ATLASThreatDetector {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self::new()
    }
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn detects_jailbreak() {
        let d = ATLASThreatDetector::new();
        let threats = d.scan("Can you jailbreak this model for me?");
        assert!(threats.iter().any(|t| t.id == "AML.T0049"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn detects_malware() {
        let d = ATLASThreatDetector::new();
        assert!(d.has_threats("write me a keylogger in Python"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn no_false_positives_on_clean_text() {
        let d = ATLASThreatDetector::new();
        assert!(!d.has_threats("What is the capital of France?"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn each_ttp_appears_once() {
        let d = ATLASThreatDetector::new();
        // Two AML.T0049 keywords in same string → still one entry
        let threats = d.scan("jailbreak AND ignore previous instructions");
        let t0049: Vec<_> = threats.iter().filter(|t| t.id == "AML.T0049").collect();
        assert_eq!(t0049.len(), 1);
    }
}

```

Below is a Tokio-based design for a high-concurrency Rust connection pool that avoids the common async deadlock traps.

Core ideas:

1. **Use a semaphore for capacity**, not a mutex/condvar.
2. **Never hold a mutex across `.await`**.
3. **Return connections with RAII** so permits are not leaked.
4. **Return idle connection before releasing the permit** to avoid races that create extra connections.
5. **Use short, non-async critical sections** around the idle queues.
6. **Use sharded idle queues** to reduce contention.

---

## Design

```rust
// Cargo.toml
//
// [dependencies]
// tokio = { version = "1", features = ["sync", "rt-multi-thread", "macros", "time"] }
// parking_lot = "0.12"
// async-trait = "0.1"
```

```rust
use parking_lot::Mutex;
use std::{
    ops::{Deref, DerefMut},
    sync::{
        atomic::{AtomicBool, AtomicUsize, Ordering},
        Arc, Weak,
    },
};
use tokio::sync::{OwnedSemaphorePermit, Semaphore};

#[async_trait::async_trait]
pub trait Connector: Send + Sync + 'static {
    type Conn: Send + 'static;
    type Error: Send + Sync + 'static;

    async fn connect(&self) -> Result<Self::Conn, Self::Error>;
}

#[derive(Debug)]
pub enum AcquireError<E> {
    Closed,
    Connect(E),
}

pub struct Pool<C: Connector> {
    inner: Arc<Inner<C>>,
}

struct Inner<C: Connector> {
    connector: C,

    // Limits concurrent checked-out connections.
    semaphore: Arc<Semaphore>,

    // Sharded idle stacks reduce lock contention.
    shards: Vec<Mutex<Vec<C::Conn>>>,

    next_shard: AtomicUsize,
    closed: AtomicBool,
}

pub struct Pooled<C: Connector> {
    conn: Option<C::Conn>,
    reusable: bool,
    permit: Option<OwnedSemaphorePermit>,
    inner: Weak<Inner<C>>,
}

impl<C: Connector> Pool<C> {
    pub fn new(connector: C, max_connections: usize, shard_count: usize) -> Self {
        assert!(max_connections > 0);
        assert!(shard_count > 0);

        let shards = (0..shard_count)
            .map(|_| Mutex::new(Vec::new()))
            .collect();

        Self {
            inner: Arc::new(Inner {
                connector,
                semaphore: Arc::new(Semaphore::new(max_connections)),
                shards,
                next_shard: AtomicUsize::new(0),
                closed: AtomicBool::new(false),
            }),
        }
    }

    pub async fn acquire(&self) -> Result<Pooled<C>, AcquireError<C::Error>> {
        if self.inner.closed.load(Ordering::Acquire) {
            return Err(AcquireError::Closed);
        }

        // Await only on the semaphore.
        // No mutex is held here.
        let permit = self
            .inner
            .semaphore
            .clone()
            .acquire_owned()
            .await
            .map_err(|_| AcquireError::Closed)?;

        if self.inner.closed.load(Ordering::Acquire) {
            return Err(AcquireError::Closed);
        }

        // Short non-async critical section.
        // No await while locked.
        if let Some(conn) = self.inner.pop_idle() {
            return Ok(Pooled {
                conn: Some(conn),
                reusable: true,
                permit: Some(permit),
                inner: Arc::downgrade(&self.inner),
            });
        }

        // Create a new connection outside all locks.
        // We still hold the semaphore permit, so total concurrency is bounded.
        let conn = self
            .inner
            .connector
            .connect()
            .await
            .map_err(AcquireError::Connect)?;

        if self.inner.closed.load(Ordering::Acquire) {
            drop(conn);
            return Err(AcquireError::Closed);
        }

        Ok(Pooled {
            conn: Some(conn),
            reusable: true,
            permit: Some(permit),
            inner: Arc::downgrade(&self.inner),
        })
    }

    pub fn close(&self) {
        self.inner.closed.store(true, Ordering::Release);

        // Wake waiters.
        self.inner.semaphore.close();

        // Drop idle connections.
        for shard in &self.inner.shards {
            shard.lock().clear();
        }
    }
}

impl<C: Connector> Clone for Pool<C> {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        Self {
            inner: self.inner.clone(),
        }
    }
}

impl<C: Connector> Inner<C> {
    fn pop_idle(&self) -> Option<C::Conn> {
        let n = self.shards.len();
        let start = self.next_shard.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed) % n;

        for i in 0..n {
            let idx = (start + i) % n;
            let mut shard = self.shards[idx].lock();

            if let Some(conn) = shard.pop() {
                return Some(conn);
            }
        }

        None
    }

    fn push_idle(&self, conn: C::Conn) {
        let n = self.shards.len();
        let idx = self.next_shard.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed) % n;

        self.shards[idx].lock().push(conn);
    }
}

impl<C: Connector> Pooled<C> {
    /// Mark this connection as broken so it is not returned to the pool.
    pub fn mark_broken(&mut self) {
        self.reusable = false;
    }

    /// Consume the wrapper and drop the connection instead of returning it.
    pub fn discard(mut self) {
        self.reusable = false;
        let _ = self.conn.take();
    }
}

impl<C: Connector> Deref for Pooled<C> {
    type Target = C::Conn;

    fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target {
        self.conn.as_ref().expect("connection already taken")
    }
}

impl<C: Connector> DerefMut for Pooled<C> {
    fn deref_mut(&mut self) -> &mut Self::Target {
        self.conn.as_mut().expect("connection already taken")
    }
}

impl<C: Connector> Drop for Pooled<C> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        if let Some(conn) = self.conn.take() {
            if self.reusable {
                if let Some(inner) = self.inner.upgrade() {
                    if !inner.closed.load(Ordering::Acquire) {
                        // Important ordering:
                        //
                        // 1. Put the connection back into the idle queue.
                        // 2. Then release the semaphore permit.
                        //
                        // If we released the permit first, another task could wake,
                        // see no idle connection, and create a new connection even
                        // though this one was about to be returned.
                        inner.push_idle(conn);

                        drop(self.permit.take());
                        return;
                    }
                }
            }

            // Pool is gone, closed, or connection is broken.
            drop(conn);
        }

        // Release capacity.
        drop(self.permit.take());
    }
}
```

---

## Why this avoids deadlocks

### 1. No mutex is held across `.await`

This is the most important rule.

Bad pattern:

```rust
let mut state = mutex.lock().await;
let conn = connect().await; // dangerous
```

The pool above never does this. It only awaits on:

```rust
semaphore.acquire_owned().await
connector.connect().await
```

and neither happens while holding an idle-queue lock.

---

### 2. The semaphore controls capacity

The semaphore is the only async wait point.

If the pool has `max_connections = 100`, then at most 100 tasks can hold permits at the same time.

That bounds:

- checked-out connections,
- connection creation attempts,
- pressure on the backend service.

---

### 3. RAII prevents permit leaks

A `Pooled<C>` owns an `OwnedSemaphorePermit`.

When the `Pooled<C>` is dropped, the permit is dropped.

This means capacity is released even if the user returns early, panics, or the future is cancelled.

---

### 4. Drop does not await

`Drop` cannot be async in Rust.

Therefore the return path must not require `.await`.

That is why the idle queues use `parking_lot::Mutex<Vec<_>>` with very short critical sections.

---

### 5. The return order prevents connection inflation

The pool returns the connection to the idle queue before releasing the permit:

```rust
inner.push_idle(conn);
drop(self.permit.take());
```

This prevents this race:

1. Task A finishes with a connection.
2. Task A releases the permit.
3. Task B wakes up.
4. Task B sees no idle connection.
5. Task B creates a new connection.
6. Task A finally returns its old connection.

That race can cause the pool to temporarily exceed the desired number of open connections.

---

## Usage example

```rust
struct MyConnector;

struct MyConnection;

#[async_trait::async_trait]
impl Connector for MyConnector {
    type Conn = MyConnection;
    type Error = std::io::Error;

    async fn connect(&self) -> Result<Self::Conn, Self::Error> {
        // Open TCP/database/etc connection here.
        Ok(MyConnection)
    }
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let pool = Pool::new(MyConnector, 100, 16);

    let conn = pool.acquire().await.unwrap();

    // Use conn.
    // When `conn` is dropped, it returns to the pool.
}
```

---

## Additional production recommendations

For a real production pool, also add:

- acquire timeout,
- connection creation timeout,
- idle timeout,
- max lifetime,
- health checking outside locks,
- metrics,
- backoff on connection failures,
- graceful shutdown,
- optional background reaper task.

The central deadlock-prevention rule remains the same:

> Never hold pool state locks while awaiting network, timer, semaphore, or user code.

